247,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-16 13:52:33+00:00,4576441,kbandla/dpkt,5916357,sunhao2014,,,84886314,112439307,"@kbandla, I checked some of the existing codes, and found when the user update the `opts` and `data` fields of `IP` object, they'll first update the data, then following a statement which updates the length fields of the head. For instance, in `test_ip()` function of `IP` module, there are the following snippets.
``` python
    s = 'E\x00\x00""\x00\x00\x00\x00@\x11r\xc0\x01\x02\x03\x04\x01\x02\x03\x04\x00o\x00\xde\x00\x0e\xbf5foobar'
    ip = IP(id=0, src='\x01\x02\x03\x04', dst='\x01\x02\x03\x04', p=17)
    u = udp.UDP(sport=111, dport=222)
    u.data = 'foobar'
    u.ulen += len(u.data)
    ip.data = u
    ip.len += len(u)
    assert (str(ip) == s)
```
Please notice when the user updates the `data` field, he'll manually update the `len` field.

At first, I plan to add some setters with `@property` decreator, however this implementation would affect the existing client code. I think this is an issue need to be discussed.

One alternative solution is add some setters explicitly, which look like `set_opts_with_len()`, to update the `opts` field and `len` field simultaneously.  Or do you have any good ideas for this problem?",{},,User,False
248,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-02 19:10:28+00:00,4576441,kbandla/dpkt,4346404,gendx,,,178970830,264536468,"Thanks for your feedback!

