848,IssueCommentEvent,2016-07-29 18:10:33+00:00,27283062,ktbyers/netmiko,899716,ktbyers,,,166927423,236252992,"Here is a link to testing:

https://github.com/ktbyers/netmiko/blob/master/TESTING.md

This is pretty close to the normal tests I run (it is actually a slightly expanded version of this):

https://github.com/ktbyers/netmiko/blob/master/tests/test_suite.sh


I need to add both a Linux server driver into this and an SSH proxy specific test into this. I have a quick linux test script which I sometimes run which is as follows (not using py.test but just running some Netmiko actions):

```
#!/usr/bin/env python
from __future__ import print_function
from __future__ import unicode_literals

from netmiko import ConnectHandler
from datetime import datetime

device = {
    'device_type': 'linux',
    'host': 'some_machine.compute.amazonaws.com',
    'username': 'admin',
    'use_keys': True,
    'key_file': '/home/admin/.ssh/test_rsa',
} 

start = datetime.now()
net_connect = ConnectHandler(**device)
print()
print(""Test find_prompt: "")
print(net_connect.find_prompt())

print()
print(""Test enable: "")
net_connect.enable()
if not net_connect.check_enable_mode():
    raise ValueError(""Not in enable mode"")
print(net_connect.find_prompt())

print()
print(""Exit enable: "")
net_connect.exit_enable_mode()
if net_connect.check_enable_mode():
