1562,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-05 22:58:45+00:00,6002572,santoshphilip/eppy,2014885,santoshphilip,,,20186945,292021139,"@SriramK89 , to add further to the comments. `Eppy` is designed to be used in the following ways:

- one-off scripting. There is something you want to get done just once.
- Scripts that are reusable
- Build an API on top of the `eppy` API.
- use the API to build an interface.
- and other stuff I haven't thought of.

if you are starting off with python, I would suggest that you start thinking about unit testing. It entails a different way of thinking about code. See http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3371255/writing-unit-tests-in-python-how-do-i-start. I learnt unit testing from http://www.diveintopython.net/unit_testing/index.html

if you want to build a quick and dirty IDF interface, use bottle.py - https://bottlepy.org/docs/dev/. Extremely simple to work with. I built one as a way of trying to understand how the objects in the idf are connected to each other. I was trying to build a better API to build HVAC. You can take a look at the code here https://github.com/santoshphilip/weppy. You can even use it here https://weppy.herokuapp.com (this may be slow to start up - I am using a free service)

Django has a more bells and whistles, would be good to use if you want a more sophisticated interface - it has a better toolkit to build things.

As you build your API, you may run into things that you wish that `eppy` had in it's API. At that point open an issue here. It will get written or we will help you write it.

",{},,User,False
