2060,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-04 09:12:56+00:00,21791607,maxtepkeev/architect,3032449,maxtepkeev,,,271054850,341882790,"Hi,

This is called list partitioning, i.e. when you have a list of choices to choose from. Unfortunately it isn't supported by Architect yet, but if you're PostgreSQL you can overcome this limitation by using [string_firstchars](http://architect.readthedocs.io/features/partition/postgresql.html#string-firstchars) range partitioning.

You need to have a column that will contain a type of the list, for example `list_type` and the values can be `white`, `black`, `general`, first_income` and so on and this is the column you should partition your table with using string_firstchars as type and put some big number inside the `constraint` option, e.g. 20, otherwise if you put a number like 5, you will end up with partition `first` for the list type first_income, `gener` for general and so on, so you need a number which is equal or bigger than your longest list type name.",{},OWNER,User,False
