2410,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-27 07:35:56+00:00,97002861,ljvmiranda921/pyswarms,12949683,ljvmiranda921,,,354093918,416141616,"> I wonder if it might suffice to use a VelocityHandler. If the particles don't even leave the bounds there is no reason to fix the position thinking Maybe we can try it out like that?

I think the two handlers solve different problems. Our perspective now should shift from ""how to prevent particles from going out-of-bounds"" into ""what happens when they're out of bounds?"" 
The `BoundaryHandler` dictates what happens whenever we go out-of bounds, ""reflective"" does this nifty trick, ""resample"" does another, etc. Of course, after changing the position, we also have to deal with the velocity that caused this potential-out-of-bounds, that's when `VelocityHandler` comes in. 

I think having the two improves particle exploration, making them less likely to be stuck in a local minima. ",{},OWNER,User,False
