3255,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-31 10:50:15+00:00,81488128,siddhantgoel/streaming-form-data,79892,siddhantgoel,,,327919320,393492462,"> I would prefer to have this functionality outside the parser.

The problem right now is that raising exceptions in targets leaves the parser in an unknown state (at the moment there is no error handling in the parser, so if targets make a mess, you are not sure what state the parser would end up in). This is something I'd really really like to avoid.

And if you're introducing error handling for errors (or failed checks) in the targets, there are 2 alternatives -

1. Either you handle the exception in the parser. Such exceptions would have to propagate from the `Target` object over to the `Part` object over to the `Parser` object. I have a feeling such a change would be messy. And it now requires that the `Parser` is aware of what the `Targets` want to do (with a `Part` object being a ""bridge"" in the middle), which feels like a dependency in the opposite direction.

2. Or you handle the exception in the target itself and make it stop processing further data. In this case the parser still keeps sending data over to the target. This defeats the whole point, at least for the `max_size` use case, since the parser is still working when the target knows that the input is invalid.

Thoughts? Third alternative?",{},OWNER,User,False
3256,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-16 09:49:44+00:00,81488128,siddhantgoel/streaming-form-data,79892,siddhantgoel,,,323515999,389461805,"First off, thanks for looking into this! Speed issues (particularly when processing larger files) is something I'm aware of but just haven't had the time recently to look into. :100: 

1. Absolutely, speed improvements are extremely important.
2. Before doing a rewrite in C, I would propose reducing the number of Python-space operations that Cython is compiling. If you open `annotation.html` in a browser, the lines highlighted in yellow are the ones that Cython couldn't generate optimized code for. And as a result, the performance is not what it could be. I would love to see if there's a way to rewrite those highlighted lines using some other primitives that Cython provides, so we can get optimized code out.

In general I'm not at all opposed to C code if that's the only way out.

But I would first like to explore if there are incremental operations possible (like reducing the Python-space operations) that improve performance.

What do you think?",{},OWNER,User,False
