3275,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-19 20:15:02+00:00,1643611,daviddrysdale/python-phonenumbers,457208,daviddrysdale,,,161077410,227017916,"If you know the country that the number is dialled from, then parsing relative to that country should work:

```pycon
>>> x = phonenumbers.parse(""009654835665"", ""GB"")
>>> x.country_code
965
>>> phonenumbers.region_codes_for_country_code(x.country_code)
('KW',)
```

If you don't know where the number is dialled from, there's more of a problem because the digit sequences aren't globally unique, i.e. the same sequence connects to different results depending on where you dial it from.

(If you knew for sure that the international dialing prefix was 00, then you might be able to replace the 00 with + and parse the number as an E.164 number -- but that's basically the same thing: to be sure the international dialling prefix was 00, you'd have to know the [country that the number was dialled from](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_international_call_prefixes)).
",{},,User,False
