6329,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-30 06:57:51+00:00,77478378,ethereum/py-evm,521109,cburgdorf,6250754,ethereum,335847949,401522364,">the fork that our top peer is on

Just so that I'm 100 % clear I understand it correctly. What fork our top peer is on, is a question of interpreting their highest block number, right? So, basically we would see that peer x is on block 7m and then lookup in our mapping and say ""oh block 7m, that is fork LazorRazorSuperman"".

If that is the case, doesn't that mean we are putting a lot of trust into whatever that peer tells us their block number is. My understanding is, that during that time (**we** aren't synced yet!), we haven't validated the entire blockchain yet and hence can't make a statement about whether that peer is trying to fool us or not. E.g. if a peer would trick us to believe that a fork has already happened even if it hasn't, the same peer could trick us to relay lots of transactions that are invalid on Byzantium but are valid on the next fork which is still far out (just because that one peer made us believe that fork has already happened but which is a lie)

>You've piqued my interest, please share! :)

I guess a lot of the things aren't much of a surprise to you but where interesting to me. Here's a super quick brain dump (because I'm about to leave for ECDC Day 2)

1. Having a scoring mechanism (needs more investigation)
2. Logic around replacing tx (nonce, gas price)
3. I think if I didn't misread, Parity seems to relay on a fixed interval rather than immediately as they arrive which seems to make sense and is probably something we also want to do (seems more resource friendly)

Probably tons of other things that I forgot again. I will continue to research parity and geth as we progress with the tx pool.
",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
