6371,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-23 11:48:59+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,897680,ukoethe,6392739,conda,129222230,187668484,"@mcg1969 @ijstokes 
>  We need to allow ""broken links"".

I'm not yet convinced. I'd agree with your point of view if calling a conflicting package resulted in an error message like ""Package xyz is outdated. Please call 'conda update xyz' to get the newest version"" (the analog of a ""page not found"" error in your web analogy). However, in practice ""broken link"" often means that there is a subtle binary incompatibility between C++ extension modules (i.e. shared libraries) which causes a mysterious crash without useful error message whatsoever. In my experience, debugging these crashes takes forever, and enforcing DLL consistency in the first place is much more efficient. Also note that a major user group of our software are biologists, who are able to use conda properly, but lack the skills to differentiate between a DLL incompatibility in the installation environment and a normal software bug.

At the moment, I'd like to be able to configure a 'strict' installation policy that would refuse to execute conda commands which might break dependencies of already installed packages. When an installation fails this way, I can easily work around the problem by creating a new environment. This is much cleaner than crossing fingers in the hope that things will *typically* not break.

In the long run, the ideal solution might be a web-accessible database (e.g. at anaconda.org) of *known* compatibility information. The database will be filled by running test suites with different combinations of package versions and applying diagnostic tools such as [ABI Compliance Checker](http://lvc.github.io/abi-compliance-checker/). 'conda install' would then first consult the database, and only resort to the current heuristic policies if the database lacked the necessary information for the present situation. I know that this sounds like science fiction, but in the long run empirically derived compatibility information is probably the only clean solution without being overly restrictive.",{},,User,False
