6404,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-13 23:45:23+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,281788570,351561780,"On unix, if the process is running under UID 0, it'll scan all home directories for the `.conda/environments.txt` file.  Otherwise, just the current user's `~/.conda/environments.txt` file.  That, in addition to looking at whats configured for `envs_dirs`.",{},OWNER,User,False
6405,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-15 15:24:19+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,11887492,justlurking,6392739,conda,256104418,329814804,"@jaimergp Thanks for weighing in. I guess there aren't too many brave fish users who have tried 4.4.0 yet. :worried:

I'm new to conda, but as I understand it based on @kalefranz's [Google Groups post](https://groups.google.com/a/continuum.io/d/msg/conda/VC32lgaTMpw/aCfOY0cvCQAJ) (and specifically the section of that post called ""Conda Activate""), one of the benefits of 4.4.0 is no longer needing to manually fuss with setting / updating $PATH.

In fairness, he specifically calls out support for Bourne-derivative shells, so perhaps this is a known problem for fish shell users. Would be nice to see confirmation if that's the case. (Even better, a fix in the next 4.4.0 release!)

I ended up removing 4.4.0rc2 and installing 4.3.25. At first I had issues because I prepended the /miniconda3/bin/ path to $PATH (causing some issues when I wanted to access the system Python), but since I modified to appending that path, everything seems to be working well.

Addendum:
As I was the typing the above, I saw you were able to successfully install 4.4.0. Congrats! I take it you did not attempt to follow the exact instructions in Kale's post regarding no longer setting ~/miniconda3/bin/ in $PATH.",{},NONE,User,False
