6640,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-24 23:46:16+00:00,4127088,Azure/azure-sdk-for-python,1050156,lmazuel,6844498,Azure,223968822,296851978,"From version 0.31.0 of azure-mgmt-resource you should have the get_by_id, please update your package if you don't and you need it.

NSG rules will be in the azure-mgmt-network client in the [""security_rules"" operations group](http://azure-sdk-for-python.readthedocs.io/en/latest/ref/azure.mgmt.network.v2016_09_01.operations.html#azure.mgmt.network.v2016_09_01.operations.SecurityRulesOperations.get).

For instance see this [unittest](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-python/blob/master/azure-mgmt/tests/test_mgmt_network.py#L507-L510):
```python
new_security_rules = list(self.network_client.security_rules.list(
       self.group_name,
       security_group_name
))
```

Please note that `list` operation is returning a generator, that will query the Azure RestAPI when needed. This means that you can get a full list in memory like the sample above or iterate directly on it:
```python
for element in self.network_client.security_rules.list(self.group_name, security_group_name):
    print(element.id)
```


",{},,User,False
