7232,IssueCommentEvent,2016-01-11 18:23:38+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,479213,pde,9289019,letsencrypt,125152191,170641952,"This plan sounds plausible, but will require considerable care.  One thing is giving the user a clear error message (the code in `standalone.py` can be borrowed to help with this, it has a way to report what process is listening on the port if it's taken).

The cases seem like:
* you find another webserver bound on the port (fine, don't add the `Listen` statement, but do add the vhosts, and tell the use to add the `Listen` themselves if they've decided to remove the other webserver)
* you find apache itself listening on the port
* you can't bind the port for some third reason (eg, the user has customised us to run as `www-data` or similar, and we don't have the privileges to bind the port).

Make extremely sure that our test code doesn't leave the port unavailable for some period of time, becoming itself a cause of the error it was trying to prevent.  On some systems clients may be trying to connect to :443 (but maybe that's fine because we can bind to :443 without listening on it?).

Anything I've missed?",{},,User,False
