7442,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-21 18:27:00+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,759579,galuszkak,10334301,marshmallow-code,306954987,375048810,"
> Deserialization should process strings without rejecting them.

Isn't that purpose of `strict` to not make it happen? I'm kinda surprised by this statement.

@yoichi so that is our main use case, because JSON/YAML distinguish Number and String as 2 different data types, we don't want to have `'1'` be the same as `1`. We need very strict validation. 

We may argue if this should be done through `strict` param but if this isn't way to do it, I would just change it to different param name, that would include strings (maybe `allow_string` or `reject_string`. Especially if someone wants to convert from string he can do it with `strict=False`. 

What do You think about it?",{},NONE,User,False
7447,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-20 19:20:15+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,6643536,Jenselme,10334301,marshmallow-code,70313986,113806045,"> Because the distributions on PyPI have already been built, even if they are just sdists (tarballs).

This is not a big deal, we can easily remove the egg-info. Moreover, it is easier to use pypi to get the soruces (github URLs are known to change from time to time). In fedora (and I guess in many other linux distros), many python packages are built from pypi. So I also think that tests and docs should be included in the tarballs. But, this is not a big issue.",{},,User,False
7453,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-03 17:24:00+00:00,19163893,marshmallow-code/flask-marshmallow,7353689,jo-tham,10334301,marshmallow-code,114206490,153424359,"I think enhancing the docs/examples would make a better experience for new users of flask-marshmallow. 

from the readme, `all_users.data` likely can not be jsonified as indicated. Perhaps I'm missing something...

``` python
class UserSchema(ma.Schema):
    class Meta:
        # Fields to expose
        fields = ('email', 'date_created', '_links')
    # Smart hyperlinking
    _links = ma.Hyperlinks({
        'self': ma.URLFor('author_detail', id='<id>'),
        'collection': ma.URLFor('authors')
    })

user_schema = UserSchema()
users_schema = UserSchema(many=True)
```

``` python
@app.route('/api/users/')
def users():
    all_users = User.all()
    result = users_schema.dump(all_users)
    return jsonify(result.data)
    # OR
    # return user_schema.jsonify(all_users)
```

It's nice that the example is orm agnostic, but since flask-marshmallow optionally integrates with sqlalchemy it might be good to have a sqlalchemy-specific example.
",{},,User,False
