7624,IssueCommentEvent,2016-04-10 23:14:20+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,147236285,208088553,"The log runs through without crashing (but reports a little leakage). Note that you are creating new contexts (4 fresh contexts are created according to the log). You can't use expressions created in one context when accessing state owned by a different context. This is a most likely cause of crashes (and would explain the leakage as well) and it requires quite a bit of diligence on the caller to ensure that contexts are used properly. The C# and Java APIs, and the python APIs do check for proper context usage as far as we have been able to identify the proper places to check, but it could very well be that not everything is checked.

Multiple contexts are useful for multi-threading, otherwise they should not be required. If you just want to save solver state so that you can explore from that state later then it should be possible to use the same context when translating solvers. Of course, this code in Z3 could have bugs, especially as it is a very rarely used feature. 
",{},,User,False
