7666,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-19 16:47:40+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,417568,craffel,11752110,Lasagne,101793220,132691558,"> Yes, the user could have passed a named SharedVariable for W_hid_to_hid, say, ""recurrent weights"", and you'd turn it into ""recurrent weightW_hid_to_hid"" now :)

Ah, sure, that's what I was worried about, but I wasn't thinking of a way to do it!

> Instead, you should give a name to the DenseLayers you are constructing, so they will name their variables accordingly if they don't have a name yet. Something like:

> ```Python
basename = '' if 'name' not in kwargs else (kwargs['name'] + '.')
in_to_hid = DenseLayer(..., name=basename + 'input_to_hidden')
hid_to_hid = DenseLayer(..., name=basename + 'hidden_to_hidden')
```
> This would give you layer_name.input_to_hidden.W and layer_name.hidden_to_hidden.W, which would also match how they can be accessed through the CustomRecurrentLayer.

Ok, I switched to this, with the minor caveat that I believe you need to delete the `'name'` entry from `kwargs` or else it will be passed in twice, because ``**kwargs` is passed to the `DenseLayer` constructors.  I implemented this, which ended up requiring a test for full converage.  Let me know what you think.",{},,User,False
