7669,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-02 09:31:56+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,102127673,144974651,"> What I would like to do is the many to many (the encoder-decoder approach, as has been discussed here).

Just to be clear, you mean the second to last example in the illustration, right? (And not the last one, which is also labeled ""many to many"", but is not an encoder-decoder architecture?)

> Can I interpret the earlier discussion as indicating one needs to modify the scan routine in order to do this?

No, I think you'd define the encoder (which would look like the ""many-to-one"" example, with a SliceLayer(..., -1) in the end) and get its output expression via `lasagne.layers.get_output()`, then define the decoder (which would look like the ""one-to-many"" example) and set its `hid_init` to the output expression you captured before. For training, you will need to collect the parameters of the encoder and decoder with two separate `lasagne.layers.get_all_params(trainable=True)` calls.
We might refactor the code such that it's possible to directly pass a network for `hid_init`, that would make it a tad easier.
Disclaimer: I've just started with RNNs and didn't need an encoder-decoder architecture yet, so this is just what I think it will look like. But I'm not sure the ""one-to-many"" decoder is possible with Lasagne right now, maybe the only way is a ""many-to-many"" decoder like the very last example that has its input repeated.",{},,User,False
