8220,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-04 18:16:55+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,25351219,DuaneEllis-TI,16142269,openthread,250864814,334244378,"I'm not blocked here - and do not want to imply that.

I was just questioning the extension name of the included makefile (fragment)

In general, makefile extensions:  "".am"" - imply the file is processed by ""automake"" to create an ""in"" file, in the openthread case this is done by ""./bootstrap""

Various if/else/endifs in the makefile are expanded or handled by Automake

The result of (after automake) is there are often still various `@MACROS@` that remain.

In general, makefile (or file) extensions "".in"" imply they are an input file (often processed by ./configure or other tools) to produce an output file.

Most commonly in this step, the `@MACROS@` are expanded by ./configure via a giant SED operation... 


",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
