8422,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-10 12:04:44+00:00,31667038,latchset/jwcrypto,8332609,simo5,17146082,latchset,169981391,238846551,"You restricted the use of the key exclusively to 'encryption' by passing in 'key_ops': ['encrypt'] in the key definition.
If you want to use RSA-OAEP-256 you need to allow also the 'wrapKey' operation as the stack trace shows, or simply do not restrict key operations in the first place (if no key_ops or use are defined then all operations/uses are allowed).

That said RSA-OAEP-256 doesn't currently work on all systems, depending on the openssl version/python-cryptography version it may fail like this:
{{{
j.add_recipient(key, header)

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/jwcrypto/jwe.py"", line 978, in add_recipient
    wrapped = alg.wrap(key, enc.key_size, self.cek, jh)
  File ""/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/jwcrypto/jwe.py"", line 170, in wrap
    ek = rk.encrypt(cek, self.padfn)
  File ""/usr/lib64/python2.7/site-packages/cryptography/hazmat/backends/openssl/rsa.py"", line 593, in encrypt
    return _enc_dec_rsa(self._backend, self, plaintext, padding)
  File ""/usr/lib64/python2.7/site-packages/cryptography/hazmat/backends/openssl/rsa.py"", line 56, in _enc_dec_rsa
    _Reasons.UNSUPPORTED_HASH
cryptography.exceptions.UnsupportedAlgorithm: This backend supports only SHA1 inside MGF1 when using OAEP.
}}}",{},,User,False
