8473,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-03 00:19:03+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1203629,wjakob,17565521,pybind,191409168,264597411,"A progress update here:

1. The PyPy now passes 95% of the test suite 🎉 .

2. A few somewhat intrusive changes were needed to accomplish this. In the (non-PyPy) pybind11 code, when the user calls a function like ``def_property_static()`` or ``def_buffer()``, a custom metaclass or buffer API is ""snuck"" into the type after it has already been created via ``PyType_Ready`` by overwriting pointers in the type data structure. 

In PyPy, we can't get away with that sort of thing anymore. The elementary type properties must be known when it is created. Thus, I've introduced two new ``class_<>`` attributes: ``buffer_protocol`` and ``metaclass`` that must be specified if the buffer protocol or static properties are used, respectively. Omitting these will lead to an (informative) exception being thrown at module import time.

2. NumPy integration also works. There is one memory leak in ``test_to_python()`` that is potentially a PyPy bug, I plan to file a bug. Also, ``test_cast_numpy_int64_to_uint64()`` fails for reasons unknown to me.

3. PyPy really doesn't seem to like C++ types with multiple inheritance exposed via cpyext. All of the multiple inheritance-related testcases are skipped for now.

4. PyPy doesn't seem to register class docstrings for some reason.

4. I've inadvertently introduced some regressions, so this currently breaks some things on regular Python ;)

Cheers,
Wenzel",{},,User,False
8474,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-05 18:22:47+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,4459524,jagerman,17565521,pybind,169485875,237925467,"Draft of an addition to (or perhaps new section following) the ""Overriding virtual functions in Python"" documentation--I'll submit this as a PR if it sounds good.

---
When combining virtual methods with inheritance, you need to be sure to provide an override for each method for which you want to allow overrides from derived python classes.  For example, if you have the following class structure:
```C++
class A {
public:
    virtual int m1() { /* ... */ }
};
class B : public class A {
    virtual void m2(int arg) { /* ... */ }
};
```
then the trampoline class for `A` must override `m1()`, while the trampoline class for `B` must override `m2()` *and* the virtual `m1()` method inherited from `A`:
```C++
class PyA : public A {
public:
    int m1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(int, A, m1); }
};
class PyB : public B {
public:
    void m1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(int, B, m1); }
    void m2(int arg) override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, m2, arg); }
};
```

There are, however, some techniques you can use to avoid this duplication.  The first technique uses multiple inheritance, but requires changing the inheritance of `A` to be virtual for both `B` and `PyA`:
```C++
// class A: unchanged
class B : public virtual A { /* ... same as above */ };
class PyA : public virtual A { /* ... same as above */ };
class PyB : public PyA, public B {
    // no m1() override needed
    void m2(int arg) override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, m2, arg); }
};
```
Another approach that avoids requiring changing the underlying C++ inheritance to virtual is to use a templated trampoline class such as:
```C++
// class A unchanged
// class B unchanged
template <class Base = A> class PyA : public A {
    int m1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(int, A, m1, /* no args */); }
};
template <class Base = B> class PyB : public PyA<B> {
    void m2(int arg) override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, m2, arg); }
};
```
defining the classes with pybind11 using:
```C++
    py::class_<A, std::unique_ptr<A>, PyA<>> a(m, ""A"");
    py::class_<B, std::unique_ptr<B>, PyB<>> b(m, ""B"");
```

The multiple inheritance approach has the advantage of requiring less code to be generated by the compiler, while the latter approach has the advantage of not needing to change the inheritance of the wrapped class to virtual.

See example-virtual-functions.cpp for complete examples using both approaches.",{},,User,False
