8869,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-29 03:40:29+00:00,68402336,streamlink/streamlink,9669492,Vangelis66,22243823,streamlink,192052147,263467807,"Hello @beardypig :smile:

> I have added a pre-compiled version of ffmpeg to the windows installer

... where exactly is this installer to be found? 
As @RuKeBo said, latest [Nightly](https://streamlink-builds.s3.amazonaws.com/nightly/windows/streamlink-latest.exe) at AWS does not contain it, which is normal, come to think of it, 
since the compiler doesn't yet use your code...

> and I have tested it on a Windows 10 VM

I visited the [youtube-4k](https://github.com/beardypig/streamlink/tree/youtube-4k/win32/ffmpeg)  branch of your streamlink fork and the win32\ffmpeg directory doesn't contain an ffmpeg executable; but file ""README.txt"" seems to allude to v3.2 from the [Zeranoe](https://ffmpeg.zeranoe.com/builds/win32/static/) repo. 
Just a heads up to you and the rest of the streamlink dev team, regarding the Zeranoe builds: 

Up to this point, both Python 3.5.2 (x86) and the streamlink code itself is fully compatible 
with Windows Vista SP2 (my current OS). I have recently decommissioned my Windows XP desktop, 
so I can't speak about that OS (but [someone](https://github.com/streamlink/streamlink/issues/89#issuecomment-255498427) said it worked). 
When it comes to XP, the last Zeranoe build to run on that OS is: 
[**FFmpeg-git-N-78758-g5156578-x86.27-Feb-2016**](https://ffmpeg.zeranoe.com/builds/win32/static/ffmpeg-20160227-git-5156578-win32-static.7z)
and the last point release is [**3.0**](https://ffmpeg.zeranoe.com/builds/win32/static/ffmpeg-3.0-win32-static.7z)
On Vista SP2, the last Zeranoe build to run is 
[**FFmpeg-git-N-80999-gf41e37b-x86.13-Jul-2016**](https://ffmpeg.zeranoe.com/builds/win32/static/ffmpeg-20160714-f41e37b-win32-static.zip) 
and the last point release is [**3.0.1**](https://ffmpeg.zeranoe.com/builds/win32/static/ffmpeg-3.0.1-win32-static.7z)

The reason more recent builds won't run isn't, of course, due to the ffmpeg code itself, 
but due to code from one of the built-in libs, most probably libx265 :disappointed: 
E.g. FFmpeg.exe 3.2 x86 on Vista throws: 
`The procedure entry point GetNumaNodeProcessorMaskEx could not be located in the dynamic link library KERNEL32.dll`
So, if you are going to bundle an FFmpeg build with the windows installer, I see three options: 
1. Use latest Zeranoe point release, compatible with Win7+. 
In that case, XP/Vista users will be left ""broken""; the docs should point them to 
last compatible builds as I stated previously (although one should have admin 
rights to overwrite existing/not running .exe with a compatible one inside %ProgramFiles%)
2. Use FFmpeg 3.0 Zeranoe build, which is XP+ compatible
3. The devs could compile a libs-free latest point release executable and use that...

@beardypig: 
I realise this isn't the correct place to report it, but I think (according to [this](https://github.com/beardypig/streamlink-portable) repo) you are the person responsible for the generation of the portable nightly builds on [AWS](https://s3.amazonaws.com/streamlink-portable/index.html). 
I downloaded latest win32 build (baked 2 hours ago), and I can report **it is broken**: 
```
G:\Applications\Streamlink\StreamlinkPortable[byBeardypig]\streamlink-portable-l
atest-win32\streamlink>streamlink
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""streamlink-script.py"", line 6, in <module>
    shutil.copyfile(""streamlinkrc.tmp"", ""streamlinkrc"")
  File ""shutil.py"", line 114, in copyfile
FileNotFoundError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory: 'streamlinkrc.tmp'
```
To remove this error, I had to rename `streamlinkrc.default => streamlinkrc` 
but then, another error: 
```
usage: streamlink-script.py [OPTIONS] [URL] [STREAM]
streamlink-script.py: error: argument --rtmp-rtmpdump/--rtmpdump/-r: expected on
e argument
```
... and to fix that second one, I had to patch streamlinkrc: 
```
 # RTMP streams are downloaded using rtmpdump. Full path or relative path
 # to the rtmpdump exe should be specified here.
 rtmpdump=rtmpdump\rtmpdump.exe
-rtmpdump=
```
So, some more work is needed on those portable builds...
",{},,User,False
