9021,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-03 20:28:30+00:00,71482397,Parsl/parsl,5114833,annawoodard,26490185,Parsl,285793678,355118231,"Another way to categorize failures, which unfortunately is not always straightforward to tease out: transient (i.e., where a retry is helpful) vs non-transient failures. Recognizing all the different failure modes automatically is something we should aim for, but a pretty ambitious project, and the parameter space of unintentional consequences is really large. I vote to be somewhat conservative at first, at least. Sometimes the user in the best position to know transient vs non-transient, so one low-hanging fruit simplified starting point would be to allow the user to specify a mapping of particular exception classes or exit codes to number of retries. (Obviously this is just syntactic sugar for what the user could implement themselves, but I think that's what a lot of people have in mind when they ask for the feature).",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
9022,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-11 08:55:34+00:00,71482397,Parsl/parsl,280107,benclifford,26490185,Parsl,339842077,404095679,"I dug into this some more and added another check, in commit 56265fa. Also see issue #382 which reports that unknown URL schemes are silently ignored.

My main concern here is fragility of the error path:

 * when users use an unknown staging scheme, as is likely to happen when performing exploratory coding: how do I discover if a ""foo"" url scheme is supported? well, let's run some code with a ""foo"" URL - and it ""sort of"" works

 * when a developer adds in a new URL scheme. There are several places where the supported schemes are enumerated in code (in various ways) and I think it is important for future-developer-friendliness to fail properly rather than silently when they don't update one of those places
",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
